responded: The root cause of the heap buffer overflow is in `xmlDictAddString` (dict.c). The function allocates a buffer for a string pool and then, when adding a new string, it does:

```c
memcpy(pool->free, name, namelen);
pool->free += namelen;
*(pool->free++) = 0;
```

However, the check for available space is:

```c
if (pool->end - pool->free > namelen)
    goto found_pool;
```

This only checks for `namelen` bytes, but the code writes `namelen + 1` bytes (the string plus the null terminator). This can cause a heap buffer overflow if the pool has exactly `namelen` bytes left.

**Fix:**  
Change the check to `if (pool->end - pool->free > namelen)` → `if (pool->end - pool->free > namelen + 1)` (or `>= namelen + 1` for clarity), and similarly update the allocation logic to always ensure space for the null terminator.

I will now prepare the patch.

